{{EngvarB|date=July 2018}}
{{about|Caledonia as the Latin name for Scotland}}
[[File:Caledonia by Wm Hole.JPG|thumb|Personification of Caledonia by the Victorian artist [[William Hole (artist)|William Hole]]]]
'''Caledonia''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|k|æ|l|ɪ|ˈ|d|oʊ|n|i|ə}}) is the [[Latin]] name given by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] to the land in today's [[Scotland]], north of their [[Roman province|province]] of ''[[Roman Britain|Britannia]]'', beyond the [[Borders of the Roman Empire|frontier]] of their [[Roman Empire|empire]]. The etymology of the name is probably from a [[Gallo-Brittonic languages|P-Celtic]] source. Its modern usage is as a romantic or poetic name for Scotland as a whole, comparable with [[Hibernia]] for [[Ireland]] and [[Cambria]] for Wales.

== Original usage ==
The original use of the name, by [[Tacitus]], [[Ptolemy]], [[Lucan]] and [[Pliny the Elder]], referred to the area (or parts of the area) later known as ''Pictavia'' or [[Picts|Pictland]] north of [[Hadrian's Wall]] in today's Scotland.{{sfn|Moffat|2005|pp=21-22}} The name may be related to that of a large central Pictish tribe, the ''[[Caledonians|Caledonii]]'', one amongst several in the area and perhaps the dominant tribe, which would explain the binomial Caledonia/Caledonii.

[[File:Schiehallion NW ridge.jpg|thumb|The north-west ridge of [[Schiehallion]], the "fairy hill of the Caledonians".]]

The name of the Caledonians may be found in [[toponymy]], such as ''Dùn Chailleann'', the [[Scottish Gaelic]] word for the town of [[Dunkeld]] meaning "fort of the Caledonii", and possibly in that of the [[Munro|mountain]] ''[[Schiehallion|Sìdh Chailleann]]'', the "fairy hill of the Caledonians".{{sfn|Bennet|1985|p=26}}{{sfn|Watson|2004|p=21}} According to ''[[Historia Brittonum]]'' the site of the seventh battle of the mythical [[King Arthur|Arthur]] was a forest in what is now Scotland, called ''Coit Celidon'' in early Welsh.{{sfn|Lacy|Ashe|Mancoff|1997|p=298}}{{sfn|Koch|2006|p=332}}

=== Etymology ===
According to Zimmer (2006), Caledonia is derived from the tribal name ''Caledones'' (or ''Calīdones''), which he etymologises as {{"'}}possessing hard feet', alluding to standfastness or endurance", from the [[Proto-Celtic]] roots ''*kal-'' "hard" and ''*φēdo-'' "foot".{{sfn|Zimmer|2006|pp=163–167}}

=== Location ===
The exact location of what the Romans called Caledonia in the early stages of Britannia is uncertain, and the boundaries are unlikely to have been fixed until the building of [[Hadrian's Wall]]. From then onwards, Caledonia stood to the north of the wall, and to the south was the Roman province of Britannia (consisting of most of what is now England and Wales).<ref group=note>{{harvtxt|Haverfield|1911|p=987}} in Encyclopædia Britannica, though, states that "a tribe of Caledones" are "named by the geographer Ptolemy as living within boundaries which are now unascertainable".</ref> During the brief Roman military incursions into central and northern Scotland,<ref group=note>{{harvtxt|Hanson|2003|p=198}} states that the military presence of Rome lasted for little more than 40 years for most of Scotland and only as much as 80 years in total anywhere. At no time was even half of Scotland's land mass under Roman control.</ref> the Scottish Lowlands were indeed absorbed into the province of Britannia, and the name was also used by the Romans, prior to their conquest of the southern and central parts of the island, to refer to the whole island of Great Britain.

[[File:Britain.north.peoples.Ptolemy.jpg|thumb|upright|Map of the populations in northern Britain, based on the testimony of [[Ptolemy]].]]

Once the Romans had built a second wall further to the north (the [[Antonine Wall]]) and their garrisons advanced north likewise, the developing [[Romano-British culture|Roman-Britons]] south of the wall had trade relations with the [[Picts]] north of the wall, as testified by archaeological evidence, much of it available at the [[National Museum of Scotland]] in Edinburgh.

== Modern usage ==
The modern use of "Caledonia" in English and [[Scots language|Scots]] is either as a historical description of northern Britain during the Roman era or as a romantic or poetic name for Scotland as a whole.{{sfn|Koch|2006|p=332}}{{sfn|Keay|Keay|1994|p=123}}

The name has been widely used by organisations and commercial entities. Notable examples include [[Glasgow Caledonian University]], ferry operator [[Caledonian MacBrayne]], and the now-defunct [[British Caledonian]] airline and [[Caledonian Railway]]. The [[Caledonian Sleeper]] is an overnight [[train]] service from London to Scottish destinations. The [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.]] is a professional [[association football|football]] club. In music, "[[Caledonia (song)|Caledonia]]" is a popular [[folk music|folk]] [[ballad]] written by [[Dougie MacLean]] in 1977 and published in 1979 on an album of the same name; it has since been covered by various other artists, most notably [[Frankie Miller]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=1021&id=1145252003 |title=Rock and roll years: the 1970s |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=16 October 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031228163008/http://news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=1021&id=1145252003# |archivedate=2003-12-28 |access-date=2009-01-17 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dougiemaclean.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47&Itemid=71 |title=Biography |work=Dougiemaclean.com |accessdate=17 January 2009}}</ref> The web series ''Caledonia'' and associated novel is a supernatural police drama that takes place in Glasgow, Scotland.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/new-detective-drama-set-to-hit-our-screens-148142n.23126482 |title=New detective drama set to hit our screens |work=[[Evening Times]] |first=Brian |last=Beacom |date=14 January 2014 |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/television-reviews/9530-caledonia |title=Caledonia |work=[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]] |first=Andrew |last=Marshall |date=26 August 2014 |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref>

Ptolemy's account also referred to the ''Caledonia Silva'', an idea still recalled in the modern expression "[[Caledonian Forest]]", although the woods are much reduced in size since Roman times.{{sfn|Smout|MacDonald|Watson|2007|pp=20-25}}<ref group=note>The extent of the reduction is a matter of debate. This association with a ''Silva'' (literally the flora) reinforces the idea that Caledonia was a forest or forested area named after the Caledonii, or that the people were named after the woods in which they dwelt.</ref>

Some scholars point out that the name "Scotland" is ultimately derived from [[Scotia]], a Latin term first used for Ireland (also called [[Hibernia]] by the Romans) and later for Scotland, the [[Scoti]] peoples having originated in Ireland and resettled in Scotland.<ref group=note>Bede used a Latin form of the word Scots as the name of the [[Gaels]] of [[Dál Riata]]. {{harv|Bede, the Venerable Saint|1999|p=386}}</ref> Another, post-conquest, Roman name for the island of Great Britain was [[Albion]], which is [[cognate]] with the Scottish Gaelic name for Scotland: ''[[Alba]]''.

