{{other uses|Langobardia (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox Former Subdivision |native_name = {{lang|grc|Λογγοβαρδία, θέμα Λογγοβαρδίας}} |conventional_long_name = Theme of Longobardia |common_name = Longobardia |subdivision = [[Theme (country subdivision)|Theme]] |nation = the [[Byzantine Empire]] |era = Middle Ages |capital = [[Bari]] |image_map = Southern Italy, ca. 1000 AD.svg |image_map_caption = Map of Byzantine themes in Italy (yellow) c. 1000. |life_span = ca. 891 – ca. 965 |year_pre = 876 |event_pre = Byzantine conquest of Bari |year_start = ca. 891 |event_start = Establishment as a theme |year_end = 965 |event_end = Establishment of the Catepanate of Italy |p1 = Exarchate of Ravenna |flag_p1 = Simple Labarum.svg |border_p1 = no |p2 = Duchy of Benevento |flag_p2 = Gisulf II solidus 631607.jpg |border_p2 = no |s1 = Catepanate of Italy |flag_s1 = Simple Labarum.svg |border_s1 = no |today = {{flag|Italy}} }}
'''Longobardia''' ({{lang-el|Λογγοβαρδία}}, also variously Λογγιβαρδία, ''Longibardia'' and Λαγουβαρδία, ''Lagoubardia'') was a [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] term for the territories controlled by the [[Lombards]] in [[Italian peninsula|Italy]]. In the 9th-10th centuries, it was also the name of a Byzantine military-civilian province (or ''[[Theme (Byzantine district)|thema]]'') known as the '''Theme of Longobardia''' located in southeastern Italy.
==History== The term was traditionally used for the Lombard possessions, with the chronicler [[Theophanes the Confessor]] distinguishing between "Great Longobardia" (Greek: Μεγάλη Λογγοβαρδία; [[Latin language|Latin]]: ''[[Langobardia Major|Longobardia major]]''), namely the [[Lombard kingdom]] in northern Italy, and "Lesser Longobardia" (Latin: ''[[Langobardia Minor|Longobardia minor]]''), which comprised southern Italy, with the Lombard duchies of [[Duchy of Benevento|Benevento]], [[Duchy of Spoleto|Spoleto]], [[Principality of Salerno|Salerno]] and [[Duchy of Capua|Capua]], the Byzantine possessions, and the city-states ([[Duchy of Naples|Naples]], [[Duchy of Gaeta|Gaeta]] and [[Duchy of Amalfi|Amalfi]]) under Byzantine suzerainty.<ref>{{harvnb|Kazhdan|1991|pp=1249–1250}}.</ref><ref name="Pertusi181">{{harvnb|Pertusi|1952|p=181}}</ref>
In its strictest and most technical sense, the name referred to the province (''[[theme (Byzantine district)|thema]]'') which encompassed the modern [[Region of Italy|Italian region]] of [[Apulia]] and parts of [[Basilicata]], with [[Bari]] as its capital.<ref name="ODB1250">{{harvnb|Kazhdan|1991|p=1250}}.</ref> Its exact origin and evolution are not entirely clear.<ref name="ODB1250"/> After a century of almost complete absence from the affairs of the Italian peninsula, Byzantium once more began to intervene actively under [[Basil I the Macedonian]] (reigned 867–886), whose western policy aimed to clear the [[Adriatic Sea]] from [[Saracen]] raiders, re-establish Byzantine dominance over [[Dalmatia]], and extend Byzantine control once more over parts of Italy.{{sfn|Kreutz|1996|pp=41–43}} In this process, [[Otranto]] was taken from the Saracens in 873, and in 876 the Byzantines took over [[Bari]], which had been captured from its [[Emirate of Bari|Saracen rulers]] in 871 by [[Louis II of Italy]].{{sfn|Kreutz|1996|p=57}} It was probably at this juncture that the foundations of the later theme were laid, perhaps in the form of a subordinate division (''[[tourma]]'') of the ''thema'' of [[Cephallenia (theme)|Cephallenia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Kazhdan|1991|pp=256, 1250}}.</ref>
The campaigns of [[Nikephoros Phokas the Elder]] in the mid-880s and of his successors greatly expanded the area under Byzantine control, which came to include all of [[Calabria]], Apulia, and the Basilicata. Even [[Benevento]], the centre of [[Lombards|Lombard]] power in southern Italy, was captured in 891.{{sfn|Kreutz|1996|pp=63–66}} The first reference to Longobardia as a theme dates to precisely this time, but at first it appears that it was administered jointly with other European ''themata'' of the Byzantine Empire:<ref name="ODB1250"/> in 891 the first known ''[[strategos]]'' (military governor) of Longobardia, Symbatikios, was also governor of [[Macedonia (theme)|Macedonia]], [[Thrace (theme)|Thrace]] and Cephallenia, while his successor George administered Longobardia jointly with its parent ''thema'', Cephallenia.<ref>{{harvnb|Pertusi|1952|p=180}}</ref> A dedicated ''strategos'' solely for Longobardia is only attested from 911 on.<ref name="ODB1250"/> In 938 and 956, it also appears united with the ''thema'' of [[Calabria]], although the duration of this arrangement is unclear. At any rate, after c. 965, the two ''themata'' were permanently united into the new [[Catepanate of Italy]], with the [[catepan]]'s seat again at Bari.<ref name="Pertusi181"/><ref name="ODB1250"/>
The [[Varangian Guard]] fought as part of the Byzantine army in several campaigns in the area, known to them as ''Langbardland''; in their [[Scandinavia]]n homleand, their exploits are commemorated in the [[Italy runestones]].
==List of ''strategoi''== *Gregorios (876) *Prokopios (880) *Stephanos Maxentios (882–885) *Nikephoros Phokas (885–886) *Theophylaktos (886–887) *Constantine (887–888) *Georgios Patrikios (888–891) *Symbatikos Protospatharios (891–892) *Georgios Patrikios (892–894) *Barsakios (894–895) *Melissenos (899–905) *Ioannikios Protospatharios (911) *[[Nicholas Epigingles]] (914–915) *Ursileo (died 921) *Anastasios (928 × 936) *Basilios Kladon (938) *Limnogalactos (940) *Paschalios Protospatharios (943) *Malakinos (c. 950) *[[Marianos Argyros]] (955–962) *Nikephoros Hexakionites (965)
